function minAddition(s, t) {
    let sLen = s.length;
    let tLen = t.length;
    let i = 0, j = 0;
    while (i < sLen && j < tLen) {
        if (s[i] === t[j]) {
            j++;
        }
        i++;
    }
    return tLen - j;
}
```

    The algorithm maintains two pointers, `i` and `j`, to iterate through the given strings `s` and `t`. The pointer `i` iterates through the string `s` and the pointer `j` iterates through the string `t`. While iterating through `s`, if we find a character that matches the current character in `t`, we increment the `j` pointer. This is because the matched character can be a part of the subsequence we are looking for. The iteration stops when either `i` reaches the end of `s` or `j` reaches the end of `t`.

At the end, we subtract the index `j` from the length of `t`. This gives us the minimum number of characters that need to be appended to the end of `s` so that `t` becomes a subsequence of `s`.

